  OOAD | Design TinyURL 

How to design a system that takes big URLs like "https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/design-a-tinyurl-system-using-ooad-principles/" and converts them into a short 6 character URL. It is given that URLs are stored in the database and every URL has an associated integer id.

One important thing to note is, the long URL should also be uniquely identifiable from the short URL. So we need a Bijective Function.

One Simple Solution could be Hashing. Use a hash function to convert long string to short string. In hashing, that may be collisions (2 long URLs map to same short URL) and we need a unique short URL for every long URL so that we can access long URL back.

A Better Solution is to use the integer id stored in the database and convert the integer to a character string that is at most 6 characters long. The schema for which can be as given below:
Table TinyURL(
    id: int PRIMARY_KEY AUTO_INC,
    originalURL: varchar,
    shortURL: varchar
)
This problem can basically be seen as a base conversion problem where we have a 10 digit input number and we want to convert it into a 6 character long string.

Below is one important observation about possible characters in the URL.

A URL character can be one of the following
1) A lower case alphabet ['a' to 'z'], total 26 characters
2) An upper case alphabet ['A' to 'Z'], total 26 characters
3) A digit ['0' to '9'], total 10 characters

There are total 26 + 26 + 10 = 62 possible characters.

So the task is to convert a decimal number to base 62 numbers.

To get the original long URL, we need to get a URL id in the database. The id can be obtained using base 62 to decimal conversion.
Below is the JAVA implementation of this idea. It comprises of 2 classes -
  1. Shortener Class - This is the class responsible for converting long URLs to short URLs and vice-versa. The input to the methods may-be confusing as we are not directly taking the long URL input. Instead, we are taking an integer. We assume here that this integer is the ID of the database where the entry: will be kept. So, we feed this ID to convert to shortURL. That way upon converting shortURL back to this ID, we can access the longURL from the database.

    while (n > 0) {
    temp += map.charAt(n % 62);
    n /= 62;
    }
    String url = "";
    for (int i=temp.length()-1; i>=0; i--)
    url += temp.charAt(i);
    return url;
    }
    static Integer toLong(String url) {
    Integer id = 0;
    char ch;
    for (int i=0; i<url.length();i++) {
    ch = url.charAt(i);
    if (ch >= 'a' && ch <= 'z')
    id = id * 62 + ch - 'a';
    else if (ch >= 'A' && ch <= 'Z')
    id = id * 62 + ch - 'A';
    else
    id = id * 62 + ch - '0';
    }
    return id;
    }
    }

            //get shortURL
            String url = Shortener.toShort(n);
            System.out.println("Id to URL: " + url);
            
            //get longURL
            System.out.println("URL to Id: " + Shortener.toLong(url));
        }

Design Considerations
We can choose any relational DB for storing the URL pairs. However, a single DB on a single system may not be scalable, and often due to large number of requests, we need multiple machines to serve the incoming requests. We thus need a system with multiple DBs over multiple machines. We can solve this problem easily using hashing as explained below:

Consider we have n independent machines deployed to serve the requests. Each incoming longURL will then need to be serviced by one of these machines. We can have efficient load balancing algorithms to decide on which machine to transfer this request. Each machine has a unique identifier, we thereafter append this identifier to the final shortURL (to identify on which the data was stored during decoding). As an example, consider we have 4 machines providing this URL shortening service.

Conversion to shortURL - 


    

  1. Load balancing algorithms (used by load-balancers etc.) determine which machine to send the request. Say it is the 2nd one. We can also use some kind of hashing to determine a particular machine. e.g. 
    

    int machineId = longURL.hashCode() % n   //n machines
    
The request then gets transferred to the delegated machine. Finally upon shortURL generation, we prepend the machine ID to the beginning separated by some delimiter. e.g. if shortURL was 'shjvk', we add '2-shjvk', to identify that machine #2 fulfilled the request
    

    2. 

  2. Conversion back to longURL - Whenever we recieve a shortURL that we need to decode, we identify the machine no. for the shortURL (the part before the delimiter), and then we access that particular machine.

     OOAD | Design BookmyShow 
 

 

 

 

 BookmyShow design is an important OOP design problem asked by many companies. The objective is to check how well the candidate is able to design a real-life problem using OOP principles. We need to fulfill the following requirements for the application - 


    

  1. Provide an interactive interface to the user to book tickets
    2. 

  2. Choose movies of different languages
    3. 

  3. Choose movies from different showtimes
    4. 

  4. List of theaters with showtimes for movies
    5. 

  5. Live booking based on Seat availability
    6.

How to handle the cases where two persons are trying to access the same seat almost same time?

The above application Main-Class instance can be run on many user devices. To prevent race conditions and undefined behaviour during booking. i.e. When two persons are concurrently trying to book a ticket, we use the synchronized keyword of the Java language. Marking an object and a corresponding block as synchronized means only one particular instance can execute that particular block. e.g. for the above Main-Class, during the time of booking (i.e. the part where we decrement seat count), we put synchronized as -

synchronized(show) {
    if (show.seats > 0) {
        show.seats--;
        System.out.println("Booking Successful\n"
                + "Movie: " + movie.name + "\n"
                + "at show-time: " + show.dateTime.toString()
        );
    }
    else
        //Otherwise report no available seats
        System.out.println("No available seats");
    break;
}

Only in actual server implementation of the Thread model, the behavior of the synchronized method can be seen.
